Here's an example of how you can create a simple search bar using PHP and HTML.

First, let's create the basic structure of our search bar:

```php
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Search Bar</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        }

        #search-bar {
            width: 50%;
            padding: 10px;
            border: 1px solid black;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }

        #results {
            margin-top: 20px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<h2>Search Bar</h2>

<form id="search-form" method="post">
    <input type="text" id="search-input" name="search" placeholder="Search...">
    <button type="submit">Search</button>
</form>

<div id="results"></div>

<?php
// Define an array of results
$products = array(
    "Product 1",
    "Product 2",
    "Product 3",
    "Product 4",
    "Product 5"
);

if (isset($_POST['search'])) {
    // Get the search query from the form input
    $query = $_POST['search'];

    // Use a simple LIKE query to find matching results
    $results = array_filter($products, function ($product) use ($query) {
        return strpos(strtolower($product), strtolower($query)) !== false;
    });

    // Display the search results
    if (!empty($results)) {
        echo "<h2>Search Results:</h2>";
        foreach ($results as $result) {
            echo "<p>$result</p>";
        }
    } else {
        echo "<p>No results found.</p>";
    }
}
?>

<script>
    document.getElementById('search-form').addEventListener('submit', function (e) {
        e.preventDefault();
        var searchInput = document.getElementById('search-input');
        var query = searchInput.value.trim();

        if (query !== '') {
            // Make a new request to the server
            fetch('/search', {
                method: 'POST',
                headers: {'Content-Type': 'application/x-www-form-urlencoded'},
                body: `search=${query}`
            })
            .then(response => response.json())
            .then(data => {
                console.log(data);
                // Update the UI with the search results
                var resultsDiv = document.getElementById('results');
                resultsDiv.innerHTML = '';
                data.forEach(result => {
                    var resultElement = document.createElement('p');
                    resultElement.textContent = result;
                    resultsDiv.appendChild(resultElement);
                });
            })
            .catch(error => console.error(error));
        }
    });
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

This example includes:

1.  A basic HTML structure for the search bar.
2.  CSS styles to improve the appearance of the search bar and its results.
3.  PHP code that processes a form submission, retrieves matching products from an array based on the search query, and displays the results in the `#results` div.

**Note**: In this example, we're using a simple LIKE query to match the search query with each product name. This may not be efficient or suitable for large datasets. Consider using a more robust solution like Elasticsearch if you have a large number of products.

To make it work on your server:

1.  Save this code in an HTML file (e.g., `search-bar.html`).
2.  Open the file in a web browser.
3.  Enter a search query, and click the "Search" button to see the results.

**Remember:** This is just a basic example to demonstrate how you can create a simple search bar using PHP. You should adapt it according to your specific needs, such as integrating it with a database or handling more complex queries.

